<TEXT>
a 23yearold student on a hunger strike 
to protest being conscripted was found guilty of insubordination 
and sentenced to five years in prison a military court spokesman 
in this northern city said friday 
the man thanassis makris a conscientious objector had asked 
to do social work as an alternative to serving the regular 24 
months in the armed forces 
maris was sentenced thursday and appealed according to the 
spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity he was jailed 
pending an appeal court hearing makris an economics student at 
athens university gave up his students privilege to defer 
military service he appeared weak at the hearing from a hunger 
strike he started 19 days before the spokesman said 
military service is compulsory in greece and there are no 
alternative options for conscientious objectors who are routinely 
given harsh jail terms 
premier andreas papandreous socialist government has pledged to 
amend a set of tough military laws on noncombatant military 
service 
the pledge was in response to a hunger strike by conscientious 
objector mihalis marangakis 31 who fasted for 68 days marangakis 
called off the hunger strike but is still serving a 26month prison 
term for insubordination 
the two men are greeces first conscientious objectors who are 
not members of the jehovahs witness sect more than 400 jehovahs 
witnesses are in jail for refusing military service 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

