<TEXT>
attorney general edwin meese iii plans to find 
a replacement quickly for a top justice department aide who says 
his departure has nothing to do with meeses legal problems 
charles cooper the assistant attorney general who heads the 
office of legal counsel handed in his resignation friday 
effective july 8 the department fully expects to have a 
replacement for cooper by the time he leaves said department 
spokesman patrick korten 
in terms of staffing the department is in better shape than 
most agencies around town at this point in an administration 
said korten many officials are returning to jobs in the private 
sector as president reagans term comes to an end he said 
there has been a complete turnover of personnel in key sections 
of the justice department since the march 29 protest resignations 
of deputy attorney general arnold burns and criminal division chief 
william weld 
five of burns deputies left following his resignation 
virtually emptying the deputys office and two of welds aides 
quit when he did 
earlier this month meese fired his chief spokesman terry 
eastland and the head of meeses speechwriting unit resigned as a 
result 
it took meese until this week to find replacements for the posts 
vacated by burns and weld burns successor utah trial lawyer 
harold christensen will fill the slot on an acting basis pending 
senate confirmation welds replacement edwards sg dennis jr 
the us attorney in philadelphia also will serve on an acting 
basis 
cooper doesnt have a job but wants to work for a private law 
firm he said his decision to leave was not based on the fact that 
independent counsel james c mckay is expected to issue a report in 
several weeks raising questions about meeses ethical conduct 
meanwhile the washington post citing anonymous sources 
reported in todays editions that meese met with vice president 
george bush earlier this month to discuss the political 
ramifications of the attorney generals legal difficulties 
the newspaper said the sources did not reveal what bush said 
during the discussion but said the meeting was requested by meese 
the vice president has said he would not ask meese to resign while 
the mckay probe is in progress but bush aides have said publicly 
that meese is a liability to bushs presidential campaign 
cooper said i have not formed any judgments about meese on 
the matters mckay has been examining meeses involvement with 
scandalplagued wedtech corp and a 1 billion iraqi oil pipeline 
project 
cooper praised meese as being almost exclusively responsible 
for advancing a number of issues on the reagan administrations 
conservative agenda 
in an interview cooper said he has an extraordinary 
admiration for meeses ability to withstand the controversy 
that prevails at this time in connection with mckays yearold 
criminal investigation of meese and that i have every good 
wish for him in the future 
meese thanked cooper in a letter for his loyalty support and 
special vote of confidence 
