<TEXT>
latin america with a new 
tradition of democracy and an old wariness of the united states 
is in a tricky position when it comes to panama and its military 
boss gen manuel antonio noriega 
on one hand the democracies of south and central american have 
expressed little support for noriega they consider him a throwback 
to an earlier era when military men called the shots in 
thinlydisguised dictatorships 
on the other hand these nations frown on overt attempts by the 
united states to dictate who should run a country and how he should 
do it 
their experience with washingtons alleged highhandedness goes 
back decades and is not easily forgotten 
it is little wonder therefore that their reaction to the 
breakdown of uspanamanian talks aimed at noriegas removal has 
been cautious and wavering 
the talks involved an offer from the united states to drop 
drugtrafficking charges against noriega in exchange for his 
removal as panamas leader 
washingtons two rivals in the region cuba and nicaragua have 
expressed strong support for noriega in his confrontation with the 
united states they have presented the conflict as a classic 
example of a small but proud country valiantly standing up to 
yankee imperialism 
most latin american democracies criticize noriega but stress 
that panamas people and not washington should decide who should 
