<TEXT>
bald eagles have built a nest in 
massachusetts for the first time in nearly a century but state 
officials say it could be another spring before the birds lay eggs 
the nest spotted in a red oak tree near the quabbin reservoir 
was built by a young female and ross the first male eagle the 
state raised and released in its sixyearold attempt to restore a 
breeding population of the endangered birds ellie horwitz a 
spokeswoman for the state division of fisheries and wildlife said 
friday 
no eggs have been found but she said young eagles which mate 
for life often practice building a nest a year or two before 
raising young 
what it really means is that our restoration program is 
working the way we had hoped she said 
the last active bald eagle nest in massachusetts was reported in 
1910 in the cape cod town of sandwich she said 
state biologists have been unable to get close enough to the 
female to check the band she is wearing but they suspect she may 
be a younger bird not yet of breeding age ms horwitz said it 
normally takes about five years for bald eagles to grow into 
maturity 
at least two other states with similar restoration efforts new 
york and pennsylvania now have nesting eagles according to mary 
beth moss of the national wildlife federation 
last year the group counted 8534 bald eagles in the lower 48 
states during its annual eagle census totals for this years count 
were not yet available but 34 were spotted at the quabbin 
reservoir 
