<TEXT>
yugoslavia today devalued its 
currency by 239 percent and instituted massive price increases as 
part of an austerity program instituted to battle a 170 percent 
annual inflation rate 
gasoline prices went up by an average 361 percent electricity 
by 314 percent postal services by 281 percent rail transport by 
385 percent and coal by 303 percent a government announcement 
said 
the government also lifted price controls for about 60 percent 
of the goods under a price freeze since last november it said 
those prices can now be determined by the market 
the prices of such staples as cooking oil flour and milk 
remained frozen and will continue to be under government control 
said the announcement carried by the official tanjug news agency 
the economic package also includes a reduction of wages by up to 
30 percent at a time when 80 percent of manufacturers in the 
country have already announced higher prices for their products 
devaluation price rises and wage cuts are a part of an 
austerity program decreed in conjunction with the international 
monetary fund 
in addition to seeking to eventually curb inflation the program 
intends to help repay the countrys 20 billion debt by introducing 
a more marketoriented economy inflation is expected to increase 
by between 8 and 12 percent as a result of the price increases 
the unpopular measures are likely to contribute to a further 
decline of living standards which have already fallen by onethird 
since 1980 
labor unrest is also expected to grow 
in the past several weeks after the government unveiled the 
austerity program several thousand workers staged a wave of 
strikes to protest the planned reduction of wages 
yugoslavia registered an alltime record of over 1600 strikes 
last year more than 300000 workers were involved 
the austerity program was originally scheduled to start may 15 
but the government said it was putting it off because of the lack 
of new loans expected from western creditors 
in its announcement the government did not say if it had 
obtained about 400 million of new loans from western creditors 
previously said to be necessary to start the program 
the lowering of the exchange rate of the yugoslav national 
currency the dinar which took effect today is based on the may 
27 dinar value according to the official daily exchange list 1 
is now worth 192275 dinars 
the dinar cannot be converted into foreign currencies in 
yugoslav banks 
the lower dinar is intended to improve the foreign trade 
imbalance by making yugoslav goods cheaper abroad however the 
devaluation makes imports too expensive for yugoslavs 
the last dinar was last devalued in november but it continued 
to lose its value daily against foreign currencies in relation to 
the american dollar its value has dropped over 250 percent in a 
year 
the gasoline price hike resulted from the devaluation of the 
dinar which makes foreign oil purchases more expensive in local 
currency the retail price of gasoline is now the equivalent of 
about 2 a gallon 
