jewish refuseniks are planning to demonstrate 
daily during the moscow summit to protest soviet human rights 
policy and the denials of their requests to leave the country 
many wellknown jewish activists have been allowed to emigrate 
from the soviet union under soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev 
leaving behind many others who have applied to leave 
after gorbachev came to power in march 1985 it seemed like 
his reforms would solve the problem said one of the activists 
marina durnovo 
but lately the west has been paying less attention to the 
problems of the activists called refuseniks because they have been 
refused permission to emigrate 
since the summit in washington last december the refusals 
have been pounded down like hail said durnova 
in planning to demonstrate during the summit she said our 
aim is to draw the attention of the soviet and american people to 
the problem of jewish emigration 
the usbased national conference on soviet jewry reported last 
week that 1086 jews were allowed to leave the soviet union in 
april the highest monthly total in nearly seven years 
the figure has been rising for about a year but it falls far 
short of the 1979 levels when the monthly average was about 4000 
departures 
another activist yuri semenovsky said he had conducted a 
survey of some of the estimated 2 million jews in the soviet union 
and concluded that 30 percent of them would like to leave his 
study appeared in the march issue of referendum an independent 
journal published by the press club glasnost a dissident 
organization that tests the limits of gorbachevs reforms 
