<TEXT>
morocco is making so much headway 
winning people over in this longdisputed territory that it no 
longer fears a referendum on independence among the inhabitants 
exemption from taxes and import duties development projects and 
an apparently unlimited supply of fresh water most precious of 
all commodities in the desert have helped undermine the support 
once enjoyed by the polisario independence movement 
the hardest blow suffered by polisario which algeria supports 
was the announcement may 17 that algeria and morocco had restored 
diplomatic relations after 12 years of hovering on the brink of war 
over the sahara 
algeria had pledged not to renew relations until morocco granted 
independence to the territory 
the moroccan army took foreign reporters on a fiveday tour of 
the 110000squaremile wilderness allowing them to set their own 
itinerary and talk with inhabitants at random without military 
escort 
nomadic tribes of the former spanish colony paid allegiance to 
the sultans of morocco for centuries and morocco annexed the 
territory after spain withdrew in 1975 
polisario a marxistled movement that is armed financed and 
supplied by algeria began fighting from algerian sanctuaries and 
at one time virtually overran the moroccan defenders 
its guerrillas have been unable to breach a 1500mile wall of 
sand and rock that morocco erected but defending it has cost the 
moroccans nearly 10000 men dead or wounded and an estimated 400 
million a year much of it donated by saudi arabia 
inhabitants of the region estimated at 76000 by the spanish 
colonial administration have fled to the moroccanheld cities or 
to refugee camps around tindouf an algerian oasis about 500 miles 
south of casablanca 
the united nations is trying to arrange a referendum among 
original inhabitants and their offspring on whether they want 
moroccan rule or independence 
king hassan ii proposed the referendum in 1981 moroccan 
officials say polisarios increasing reluctance to accept a 
unsupervised referendum is a measure of the movements loss of 
support among the population 
reporters saw no sign of polisario activity or support 
saharan workers in the bou craa phosphate mines saharan 
fishermen in dakhla port 800 miles south of casablanca 
shopkeepers in el ayoun the territorial capital and nomads with 
their herds of camels and goats all expressed promoroccan feelings 
and loyalty to hassan 
pictures of the monarch were displayed in their tents the king 
is both political and religious leader of morocco 
mohamed ould mbarek 65 has pitched his tent 25 miles west of 
bou craa he sold twothirds of his 100 camels to buy two 
apartments in el ayoun for his two wives so his children can go to 
the new moroccanrun schools there 
asked how he felt about polisario the graybearded bedouin 
clutched the engraved silver handle of his dagger and said angrily 
if they come here i will kill them 
in el ayoun trader mohamed khaddad said one of his eight sons 
was with the polisario in tindouf he said there had been no word 
from him in eight years and declared 
if he ever comes back i will tell him he is a traitor to his 
country and his king i pray that god may give me the strength to 
forgive him one day 
salah zemrag governor of el ayoun province said morocco has 
built schools hospitals highways artesian wells and more than 
18000 homes in the town which was little more than a military 
outpost when the spanish left 
fadli rguibi 38 is among hundreds of former polisario 
guerrillas who moroccan officials say fled across the desert from 
algeria in recent months as morale declined and camp conditions 
worsened 
of the people in the tindouf refugee camps rguibi said they 
are carefully watched and spied on they are afraid to talk freely 
among each other because anyone could be an informer but you cant 
suppress the truth forever everyone long suspected the war was 
lost only the leaders still seemed to believe in it 
polisario originally claimed the western sahara had 1 million 
inhabitants most of them in and around tindouf but now says only 
165000 refugees live in the algerian camps morocco says most are 
not saharans 
rguibi said the guerrillas number fewer than 10000 
in aousserd a desolate volcanic crater outpost 125 miles 
southeast of dakhla the reporters were taken by helicopter to a 
strongpoint on the wall 
moroccan soldiers manned french american and czechoslovakmade 
artillery and machine guns overlooking the wide empty plain 
leading into neighboring mauritania the red greenstarred 
moroccan flag fluttered overhead 
gen abdelaziz bennani commander of moroccan forces in the 
sahara said the wall was manned by 80000 men more than half the 
moroccan army equipped with sophisticated weapons and radar 
sensors 
our equipment is so sensitive he said that we recently 
picked out a truck with four tourists who lost their way in the 
desert from more than 25 miles away 
he said the guerrillas last attacked the wall jan 30 in a 
hitandrun raid without causing moroccan casualties or getting 
near the moroccan defenses 
their claims of almost daily attacks are sheer fantasy he 
said 
