<TEXT>
here are excerpts from the interview 
that president reagan gave soviet journalists for broadcast in the 
soviet union in advance of the moscow summit 
the text of the interview which was conducted before reagan 
left washington was released saturday by the white house staff in 
helsinki questions were translated from russian 
q mr president you are about to visit moscow this will be 
your first trip to our country with what feelings do you travel to 
the soviet union and what do you expect at your next summit 
reagan well this will be the fourth meeting between the 
general secretary and myself i am obviously looking forward to the 
trip for one reason because i have never been there and im 
looking forward to seeing your country and well as much as is 
possible with the meetings that will be going on and we have 
discussed in the previous meetings with your general secretary such 
matters as arms reductions and weve been successful on the one 
treaty we are both working on the present treaty that we call 
start the 50 percent reduction of intercontinental ballistic 
missiles but also some differences that weve had on our 
interpretation of human rights on regional affairs and we are 
greatly heartened by the fact that your forces are withdrawing from 
afghanistan and on bilateral issues such things as rescue at sea 
agreements fisheries agreements things of that kind in which 
weve made great progress 
q what is your view for the possibility for further advancement 
toward peace 
reagan well i have to be optimistic about it i have read 
perestroika covertocover and the goals that were outlined 
there for your own country and by your present leader were such 
that i think it would reduce some of the differences between us 
further and make it possible for future leaders of our countries 
to eliminate the well what i called for in the in our first 
meeting in geneva when just the general secretary and i were 
talking to each other i pointed out that we didnt mistrust each 
other because we were armed were armed because we mistrust each 
other and that we had a unique opportunity the two of us to go 
to work not just to try and reduce arms but to reduce the causes 
of the mistrust 
q mr president an opinion is forming in moscow that it 
would hardly be possible to sign a treaty on the 50 percent 
reduction of strategic nuclear weapons while observing the inf 
treaty and what is your perspective on the completion of such an 
agreement that would further peace 
reagan well i still think it can be concluded but it would 
be i think overly optimistic with the time limitations to believe 
that it could be ready for signature as the inf treaty was here in 
the previous meeting but were going to continue negotiating 
q do you believe that it will be signed this treaty 
reagan yes i do i dont think either of us have gone this far 
with the idea that it wasnt a good idea 
 
q could you at the beginning of your presidency when you had 
just entered the oval office imagine the possibility of your 
upcoming visit to moscow 
reagan probably not because very frankly i have to say i 
think there is a difference between this general secretary and 
other leaders of your country that i have met with in the past i 
dont think they had any dreams of perestroika and yet i felt 
that we had to exist in the world together our systems are 
different were going to be competitive in a number of ways and 
thatll continue but we can be competitive without being hostile 
to the point of conflict with each other and i think this is what 
were aiming at and no i could not have foreseen your present 
leader 
q well new times bring new leaders 
reagan yes 
q is it possible to conclude that you expect that your 
successor will continue the course of stabilization of 
sovietamerican relations that there will not be a break in the 
dialogue between our countries 
reagan well if the next president is the president i would 
like to see there the present vice president i know he would 
continue on this track but i think that our people want this i 
had a visit just the other day here in the white house with 78 
young teenagers and half of them were from the soviet union and 
half were students of ours and you looked out at those young 
people and you couldnt say well those are russians and those 
are americans you just saw young people who had learned to know 
each other exchange ideas and get acquainted and i found myself 
saying to them if all the young people of the world could get to 
know each other thered never be another war 
 
q the majority of presidents in this country at the end of 
their term of office write their memoirs are you preparing to 
write your memoirs and when can we if so get a chance to read 
them 
reagan well ive been thinking very seriously about writing a 
book in view of the fact that several people who have left 
government have written some books i think maybe id better 
straighten out the record and tell things as they really are and 
so its possible i will 
q since our time is up more or less id like to thank you for 
the interview and wish you great success in the future 
reagan well thank you very much may i just say one thing 
also in getting to your country and i would relish the 
opportunity if i could to say a few words here that is never 
discussed very much i have a great admiration for the women of the 
soviet union particularly in the russian area from the outside 
looking they seem to be a great bulwark of strength and solidity 
in the maintaining of the home in the things that they stand for 
the standing in lines to bring home what is necessary for the 
family and all of that and i just wonder if theyre getting the 
credit within your country that i think they deserve 
q they do deserve it but they dont just stand in lines the 
overwhelming majority of them work together with men 
reagan yes 
q and i hope you will be able with your own eyes to see 
all of this when you come to our country 
reagan well youve said it better than i did but yes i 
recognize all of those things and just wondered if they get the 
recognition they deserve within their own country 
</TEXT>
