<TEXT>
elaine black yoneda a communist party 
member who led labor revolts in the depression and was dubbed the 
red angel by union colleagues has died at age 81 
mrs yoneda died thursday one day after attending a union rally 
for presidential candidate jesse jackson she had been ill for a 
month 
in 1931 she moved to southern california from new york city to 
become secretary of international labor defense which provided 
legal aid to trade unionists she was a communist party member from 
1931 until her death 
one of the first people she bailed out of jail was communist 
party member karl yoneda a japanese native who changed his first 
name in honor of karl marx they were married in 1935 
she spent eight months in a japanese detention camp during world 
war ii with her husband and their son despite his detention karl 
yoneda later served as an intelligence officer in the pacific 
theater 
mrs yoneda was the only woman on the steering committee of san 
franciscos general strike in 1934 which grew out of a waterfront 
and maritime strike after two demonstrators were killed by police 
the same year she and other activists were arrested at a 
protest and jailed for vagrancy a charge dimissed after two trials 
and a hunger strike they are not vagrants an appellate judge 
ruled they are communists 
mrs yoneda was arrested on other occasions for disturbing the 
peace inciting a riot seditious utterances and unlawful 
assembly during labor and antiwar demonstrations 
from the late 1950s until she retired in 1973 mrs yoneda was a 
clerical worker for the international lonshoremens amp 
warehousemens unionpacific maritime association pension fund 
she was an active member of the office amp professional employees 
international union local 29 until this year and also was president 
of the ladies auxiliary of ilwu local 16 
she is survived by her husband a daughter and son and two 
grandchildren 
