<TEXT>
an atlas of avoidable death 
published by the european economic community showed that more than 
1 percent of deaths in the eec involving illness and childbirth are 
avoidable officials said friday 
paolo fasella the eecs head of science research and 
development said the survey tried to use mortality data as a means 
to study the health services within the eec 
the editor of the 356page book british professor walter 
holland said the number of avoidable deaths in the eec is very 
small indeed 
fasella said it amounts to about 50000 deaths a year 
holland said given the proper medical attention or public health 
action the diseases surveyed should result in very few if any 
deaths 
the survey looked at 17 illnesses including appendicitis 
hodgkins disease womb cancer tuberculosis asthma deaths 
resulting from childbirth and infant mortality 
holland cautioned that the figures only served to indicate the 
existence of problems in the eecs health sector not their nature 
the atlas cannot provide any answers but it points to areas 
for investigation he said 
he said the causes of high mortality rates were extremely 
complex but the statistics showed clearly there was no 
correlation between the money spent the organization of health 
services and the death rate in each member state 
holland head of the department of community medicine at the 
united medical and dental schools of guys and st thomass 
hospitals in london stressed a high death rate for the same 
disease in two different areas did not mean the same problem 
existed in both areas 
it merely indicates there may be a problem he said 
as an example he said deaths from womb cancer could be due to 
insufficient public health information or the unavailability of 
screening tests in that area 
only 10 of the 12 eec member states were surveyed for the atlas 
the books statistics date from 197478 spain and portugal joined 
the trade bloc in 1986 
</TEXT>
