<TEXT>
japan will seek to end a deadlock in talks with the 
united states on opening its market to foreign beef by offering new 
import duties instead of steep surcharges a japanese newspaper 
reported friday 
yomiuri shimbun said japan would offer to raise the current 25 
percent duty on imported beef to more than 70 percent its 
previous proposal rejected by us negotiators was to impose an 
additional 75 percent surcharge which would have doubled the price 
of foreign beef when sold on the japanese market 
the surcharge would have gone to a semiofficial corporation and 
be used to stabilize domestic beef prices and aid japanese farmers 
the newspaper said the new offer will be made in workinglevel 
talks in washington next week and represents japans ultimate 
compromise proposal it said the new tariff rate would continue 
for at least three years and would compensate for removal of 
present import quotas 
japanese government officials have said duties or surcharges are 
needed to protect japanese farmers if quotas are eliminated 
an official of the ministry of agriculture forestry and 
fisheries speaking on condition of anonymity said he could 
neither confirm or deny the report 
a fouryear japanus agreement setting annual increases in 
japanese import quotas on beef and citrus imports expired in march 
no new agreement has been reached in talks since then including 
talks in washington last month between agriculture minister takashi 
sato and us trade representative clayton yeutter 
sato refused to comply with a us demand that japan specify a 
short timetable for an end to the import quotas on the two items 
and sharply reduce the level of the proposed duties and surcharges 
on may 4 the united states took its case to the general 
agreement on trade and tariffs an international trade body based 
in geneva prime minister noboru takeshita and other japanese 
officials say they want to continue to seek a solution through 
bilateral talks 
