in greece for example dimitriades national political union 
won just 06 percent of the vote in the last national elections in 
1985 and that represented a drop from the 23 percent it won in 
the european parliament vote a year earlier while dimitriades won 
a seat in the european parliament in strasbourg his party remains 
out of parliament at home 
belgiums national front also has no representation in the 
nations 212seat house of representatives and is so far out on the 
fringes that it does not figure in publicopinion polls 
le pens national front holds 35 just seats in frances 
577member national assembly but he himself has been gaining over 
the years from 074 percent of the vote in the 1974 presidential 
election 11 percent in the 1984 european parliament balloting to 
144 percent in april 
gianfranco fini secretary of the vaguely neofascist italian 
social movement is optimistic about the outcome in france 
he maintains immigrants pose a grave threat to all european 
countries 
unemployment in italy is 124 percent and yet immigrants from 
africa and asia come ashore at the rate of 50000 a year although 
90000 foreigners were legally registered in october 1987 
unofficial estimates put the number of illegal immigrants at 
800000 racial animosity has risen in italy along with the 
immigration 
finis party won 59 percent of the vote in parliamentary 
elections last june it holds 35 seats in the 630member chamber of 
deputies making it italys fourth largest party but it does not 
figure prominently in the shaping of italian governments or 
policies 
even so foreign workers are an issue in italy the largest 
daily newspaper la repubblica published a survey in early may of 
high school students that it said indicated open hostility 
toward immigrants 
seventy percent of those responding said they would favor a 
partial or total closing of borders to foreigners who rob us of 
work 
in france an intellectual new right is providing a 
theoretical framework for neofascism socalled revisionist 
historians are publishing works that reexamine the country under 
nazi occupation and question whether the extermination of 6 million 
jews during world war ii actually occurred 
le pen referred to the gassing of jews in nazi death camps as 
a detail of history 
similarly in italy a spate of books and articles is reassessing 
the italy of dictator benito mussolini in the years before and 
during world war ii a leading mussolini historian has suggested 
that laws forbidding the reestablishment of the fascist party 
are anachronistic 
le pen visited rome on may 8 taking his message to a cheering 
crowd at an italian social movement meeting he plans similar trips 
around europe in the coming months said his spokesman alain vizier 
but le pens presence already has been felt abroad 
mogens glistrip leader of the denmarks antiimmigration 
progress party is frequently referred to in the press as the local 
le pen 
in danish parliamentary elections in may glistrips party took 
16 of the legislatures 179 seats up from 9 it was the second big 
gain in a row for the party which had increased its holdings from 
6 in another election last september 
norways carl i hagen also is compared to le pen he leads the 
norwegian branch of the progress party that won 122 percent of the 
popular vote in local elections last fall recent opinion polls 
give the party 15 to 23 percent making it norways second largest 
party after the governing labor party 
hagen advocates limiting immigration based on the availablity of 
housing and jobs 
political analyst ole borre of denmarks aarhus university said 
the swing to the right in denmark and norway is part of an 
international trend 
some observers contend le pens success is unique a product of 
the twotier french election process and the candidates 
personality 
greeces dimitriades says groups like his pose no immediate 
challenge to existing european democracies 
there is a swing toward conservatism in europe dimitriades 
said but its too early to say if it is swinging into our 
sphere 
