<TEXT>
editors note veteran ap reporter bob thomas covered the 
victory party that ended in death for robert kennedy here he 
recalls that night 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
after a luncheon in the empire room of the 
ambassador hotel recently i stopped at the passageway to the 
kitchen 
a bus boy was piling dishes and the thought was inescapable 
what a homely place for an event that changed the course of a 
nation 
toward midnight on june 4 1968 i was in the press room 
adjacent to the empire room my assignment for the ap the night of 
the california presidential primary was to cover the leading 
democratic contender robert f kennedy 
the polls had already reported an overwhelming victory for the 
new york senator and kennedy made his acceptance with customary 
eloquence in the empire room 
next he would cut through the kitchen to the press room to 
answer reporters questions but as i waited near the kitchen door 
there was a series of sharp reports like balloons popping 
then screams i rushed toward them 
it was a scene of terror women were wailing men yelling the 
noise reverberated so loudly that i couldnt tell what anyone was 
shouting 
in a corner i could see the athletes rafer johnson and rosey 
grier struggling with someone i had no sense of danger still not 
grasping the reason for the popping sounds i felt detached 
watching the panic as if it were a vivid movie scene 
a cluster of people stood in the center of the room peering 
down with horrified faces i couldnt see what they were looking 
at i jumped up on a stack of kitchen trays 
robert kennedy lay on the floor blood streaming from his head 
blank eyes staring into the void 
after gathering in the nightmarish scene i jumped down and 
rushed to a press room phone it was dead i ran into the hotel 
lobby where i knew there was a row of phone booths i slipped a 
dime into the first phone and couldnt get a dial tone finally i 
was able to reach the office 
bob myers aps san francisco bureau chief who was helping out 
in los angeles answered this is the conversation as he later 
related i dont remember it 
thomas i got a flash kennedy shot 
myers are you serious 
thomas im serious kennedys been shot 
myers did you see it 
thomas no but i saw him lying on the floor 
myers youre sure what exactly did you see 
thomas kennedy lying on the floor of the kitchen hall with 
blood all over his face he had been shot 
as i was dictating the story i heard a commotion in the lobby 
leaning out of the telephone booth i could see a phalanx of los 
angeles policemen hurrying a young man down the marble staircase 
right in front of me i returned to the phone and gave a 
description of the man who turned out to be sirhan sirhan 
after all the dictation i put down the phone with a feeling of 
emptiness and sorrow i walked dazedly toward the kitchen but a 
policeman blocked the entrance to a place that was now part of 
history 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

