<TEXT>
as the crash of 1987 recedes into memory wall 
streeters are sounding a new lament the stock market is too quiet 
fear of the volatility that rocked the markets last fall and in 
early 1988 appears to have created a kind of paralysis leaving 
brokers sitting by idle telephones while their customers watch and 
wait 
by all accounts the crash frightened away not only individual 
investors but also professional managers who work for pensions 
funds and other large pools of money 
in congressional testimony this past week david ruder chairman 
of the securities and exchange commission said institutional money 
managers were suffering from great fear about volatility 
through may 24 trading volume this year on the new york stock 
exchange is running 64 percent behind its pace in 1987 at the 
american stock exchange the dropoff has been 271 percent 
last monday when 10264 million shares were traded was the 
quietest session not affected by a holiday at the big board in 
nearly a year and a half 
the story is much the same in the bond market where inflation 
worries have intensified the postcrash blues david resler 
economist at nomura securities international recently calculated 
that customer transactions for primary dealers in us government 
securities were down 22 percent from their 1987 rate 
the way many analysts see it the outlook doesnt look good for 
an improvement in this situation any time soon with the dog 
days of summer approaching 
from now through labor day anyway its going to be dull 
said raymond f devoe jr at legg mason wood walker inc 
in such a climate morale on wall street is naturally low the 
wall street journal reports that one major investment firm kidder 
peabody amp co is considering putting some of its traders on a 
fourday work week this summer although the firm denies that 
by their very nature traders want immediate gratification 
observed william king head of equity trading at nikko securities 
international 
in bull markets there is plenty of that with abundant 
activity and many stories but bear markets see little activity and 
less information 
traders give up quickly on their positions that is why we see 
such sleepy trading rooms 
viewed from a historical perspective the numbers might not 
appear to warrant so much gloom although average volume on the 
nyse reached 18894 million shares in 1987 it averaged less than 
100 million shares a day as recently as 1984 ten years ago it was 
less than 30 million shares 
so a casual observer might regard the current slump as no more 
than a modest retrenchment after a long period of explosive growth 
in truth wall streeters like people in a good many other 
businesses are known for a tendency to hyperbole when they talk 
about their problems 
but analysts also point out that the recent slowdown is a very 
real threat to jobs and profits in an industry that had expanded 
