a steep drop in americans april disposable income and a 
slowdown in consumer spending have not eased investor fears of 
higher inflation or dissuaded economists from forecasting higher 
growth this year 
disposable personal incomes fell 09 percent last month the 
largest drop in a year and the first decline in that category since 
last november the commerce department reported friday 
economists attributed the decline to higher tax bills which 
also compelled many consumers to resist big purchases last month 
that left spending basically unchanged in april after a 08 percent 
rise in march 
before adjusting for taxes personal incomes edged up a tiny 01 
percent in april after a giant 11 percent rise in march 
the weak income growth and stagnant spending figures ordinarily 
would be regarded as signs of a slowing economy but economists 
said the april tax payments along with an early easter helped 
depress consumer spending one of the key engines of economic 
growth 
